  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under federal law, money laundering can result in significant criminal penalties. Generally, these include:\n\n1. Monetary Penalties:\n- Substantial fines (often up to $500,000 or twice the value of the property involved)\n\n2. Criminal Penalties:\n- Prison sentences typically ranging from 10-20 years\n- Maximum sentences can extend up to 30 years depending on specific circumstances\n- Potential consecutive sentences for multiple related charges\n\n3. Additional Consequences:\n- Asset forfeiture\n- Potential civil penalties\n- Loss of professional licenses\n- Permanent criminal record\n\n4. Factors Influencing Sentencing:\n- Amount of money involved\n- Sophistication of the laundering scheme\n- Prior criminal history\n- Role in the offense\n\nSpecific penalties depend on the exact statute violated (18 U.S.C. \u00a7\u00a7 1956 and 1957) and case details.\n\nNote: This is general legal information, not specific legal advice. Actual penalties can vary based on individual case circumstances.",
